@node Introduction "Intro to Graphic Workbench"

      Hello and welcome to the wonderfull world of Graphic Workbench

  Relax, sitback and let The Conspiracy enhance your dreary old Workbench


             OK first things first, thanks for taking an interest in Graphic
Workbench we hope you will find this program of some use to you.
             Graphic Workbench is a program that places a backdrop of your
choice into your WBPattern, and whatever backdrop you have chosen a set of
corresponding icons will be added as your partition icons. The excellent
program WBVerlauf by Christian A. Weber will also be added and set up so it
blends in with your backdrop. Each backdrop will have it's own WBverlauf
configuration.
             No backdrop will be placed in your windows, but if you wish you
can set it up so as the pic showing on your Workbench will also be displyed
when you open a window. Alternativly on disk 1 you will find a directory
called "WindowPics" in there you will find some tile size pics of various
Amiga logo's etc that will use far less memory than a full backdrop. Be
warned though that some logo's may cause a colour clash with the newly
configured palette, so choose wisely young jedi knight.
             In essence what you have here is a demo, although Disk 1 is
the main program and will never change, Disk 2 is a selection of backdrops
and icons taken from a series of @{"Data Disks" link Data Disks} that cover individual subjects
ie. Glamour, Sci-Fi, Fantasy, WbPattern, Games etc.
             This demo disk has a selection of 10 backdrops & icons, there
should be something on here for all tastes whether you're into starTrek
or Fantasy or even nice pieces of tottie.
            @{b} DOOM on the Amiga @{ub}- Well not quite, we may not have the
game running on our Amiga's but now you can have the backdrop & icon set
sitting on your workbench screen and it's on the Demo Disk so run along now
children.

@endnode

@node Requirements "Requirments for Graphic Workbench to run"

           You will need an AGA Amiga with a HD, and although not essential
some extra memory would be a help.

           Where we believe our program stands out from the rest is our
Partition Icons are designed specifically to complement the selected
backdrop giving your Workbench a much more Graphically pleasing look. To
achieve this it may take up that bit more memory but we believe the results
justify this.

           As we said earlier extra memory is not essential but you'll be
amazed by the difference an extra 2mb fast ram makes. When the Amiga 1200
was first launched 2 MB Ram sounded massive, but how big is it once you've
fitted a Hard Drive, after Workbench boots up your lucky if you have 1 Mb
left just try running Image FX, Photogenics, or even just compressing files
with LHA it's a nightmare. We personally use the Viper board and The
Blizzard 1220/4 satisfaction gauranteed. The only trouble the 1220/4 caused
was on incompatibility on Macks @{"system" link Systems} with the Zappo CD Rom drive. Although
that has now been solved with the release of the latest install software
v12 from Archos.
           So make the leap, invest in FAST Ram today & support The Amiga
@endnode

@node Installation "How to install Graphic Workbench"

@{b}How do I Install Graphic Workbench?  @{ub}
           
              Installation could not be simpler, the first time you load
Graphic Workbench you will be given two choices you can either A. View all
the backdrops before making your choice or B. Install a backdrop & icon set
there and then. Obviously if you have just booted up for the first time you
will wish to view the backdrops first before making your choice.

@{b}What files will be placed on my Hard Drive?@{ub}

              If this is the first time using the program  we will save your
old icons & system configurations etc in a Directory called T.M.C this will
be created in your SYS:Prefs partition so your old icons can be re-installed

              The program wbverlauf will be placed in the
WBstartup drawer. And the new icons to match the backdrop you chose will be
renamed as Disk.info and placed in the appropriate partition.
 Your WBPattern & Screenmode prefs will also be changed so as to show of the
backdrop & icons at the correct configuration

@{b}What do I need to do to view the Backdrop & Icon set I selected?@{ub}

              Simply reset your computer the computer needs to be reset so 
so the workbench screen can remap itself into the colours used by the
backdrop. After a simple reset you then see your selection in all it's glory

@{b}What has happened to my old icons?@{ub}

              Your old Icons and backdrop (if you had one) are quite safe
and have been saved and placed in a Drawer called T.M.C which can be
found in the Prefs Drawer in your Workbench partition.

@{b}Why does it hurt when I urinate?@{ub}

              You have Cystitis "That be a womans disease"

@endnode

@node Usage "How to use Graphic Workbench"

How do you use Graphic Workbench? Bit of a stupid question really, as once
it's installed all you can do is sit back and admire (we hope).
Anyway as there is no real usage to describe, we "The Conspiracy" would like
to take this opportunity to tell you (in the form of an @{"Advertisment" link Advert} ) some
of the wonderful things already said about Graphic Workbench.

Johnny (the lad down the road)  - It's Wonderful I especially like the Red
                                  Dwarf one it's the best.
July-Ann (Tearaway 1)           - It's probably the best thing thats
                                  happened to me.
Vicky (Tearaway 2)              - My life was an empty barron shell but now
                                  I feal complete, at peace with the world.
Bob Byers (He sells spare tyres)- I thought I had seen everything but when
                                  I laid my eyes on Graphic Workbench my
                                  @{"Trousers" link Trousers McBurnie} went all moist.
Mr J.Thompson (Vicar)           - I'm convinced it's a major contribution
                                  to road safety.
Davey Bed (Mitsubuishi bod)     - My black & decker certainly noticed the
                                  difference. !!??
The East Lothian Courier        - Puerile nonsense written by half-wits

I've just remembered a bit of information that may be helpfull in using
Graphic Workbench, each backdrop has 6 accompanying icons (we figure not
many people have more than 6 partitions). On some icons it has the
partition names written on them ie. SlaineIvory has some stunning icons with
dh0, dh1, ram etc written in the top corner, the ram icon obviously is not a
problem  but if your one of those people whose partitions are named
differently ie HD1 or bobsdrive 1 etc you will find the 6th icon "Default"
is identical to the rest with exception of missing out the partition name
So you could use this icon to replace all partition icons or you could use
a program such as iconian and adjust the icons to suit.

NOTE. Any backdrop set that has icons with the partition names written on
them will have a default icon that has no partition name on it.



@endnode

@node History "How old is Graphic Workbench"

             This the first release of Graphic Workbench, hopefully it will
be an ongoing process with the release of Data Disks.

             Graphic Workbench is really @{"The Complete Picture II" link Author} but with
a much better user interface and a WB3 look.

             When we first started work on GWb we were not sure what form it
should take, initially it was going to be 3 disks with 2 of the disks
packed with as many backdrops and icons as we could fit on. Gradually we
decided that only 2 disks was a much better idea, Disk 1 being the main
program and disk 2 being a demo of some of the backdrops and icons available
through the@{"Data Disks" link Data Disk}. This also had the added bonus of being cheaper to
post.

@endnode

@node Author "Who wrote Graphic Workbench and Why?"

Graphic Workbench was written by The Surgeon from an original idea by Mack.

            The idea behind Graphic Workbench came after reading Amiga Format
and seeing in their "Workbench" section pictures of Amiga Workbench's with
brill pictures adorning the background, a quick check of the shit Amiga
manual informs me I can place a picture in the WBPattern and it will be
displayed every time I bootup.....Amazing!!!

            It started there really, we first brought out"Backdrop Stramash"
which was just 12 pictures that you would have to install yourself and to
be honest was pretty poor. Then came "The Complete Picture" which we felt
was a pretty good program but it never really took off. Ironically it is now
just appearing in the adverts for PD Houses. The reason we think TCP never
really flourished was A. We never distributed it well enough. B. It wasn't
as stable as Gwb ie. if you installed a backdrop and icon set it used to
just delete your old ones to hell. and C. the name was shit if you see
Graphic_Workbench listed in an advert you have a rough idea what it is,
I don't think you can say the same for The Complete Picture.

            The Surgeon took nearly 10 months to write the installer and all
the programming bits for this program, God knows what took so long.
ps from the Surgeon  A voice in my ear kept saying "I Think We Should Change
That Picture For This One "
            If you have any queries or have found a bug or you just want to
have a chat with the Surgeon then contact him via:
