@node Drivenames "DRIVE NAMES"

       @{b}  If Your Drives Are Not Called Dh0: Dh1: Dh2: etc @{ub}

Hopefuly if this is the case you copied the origanals first and never ruined
them  {if so send them to us telling us your partition names} this program
needs to know the partition names as in dh0: jh0: hd0: etc not the pet names
as in workbench: work: games: etc

 If you are unsure about the partition names open up a SHELL or CLI window
this can be found in the systems drawer type the word INFO then press
return you will find the information you require here remember if it starts
with the letters DF then it is probaly a floppy disk drive ignore ram:
ignore cc0 as this is whatever is pluged into your PCIMA slot now you should
be left with the partition names we are looking for

          @{b} @{i} Take a note of them and run Graphic_Workbench again @{ui} @{ub}

                           @{ "BACK TO PROBLEM PAGE" link problems }
@endnode
@node ramicon "RAM.ICON"

You will probaly find the computer has stored a ram icon somewhere this is
usually found in your main partition or in the s directory under the name
ram.info if you look in your startup-sequence or user startup you may find
a line telling the computer to copy ram.info or disk.info to ram: put a
semicolon ; in front of this line and reboot the computer This should solve
your Problem



            @{ "HOW DO I EDIT MY STARTUP-SQEUENCE OR USER-STARTUP" link edit}



                           @{ "BACK TO PROBLEM PAGE" link problems }
@endnode

@node iconcolours "ICON COLOURS RUBBISH"

The only time we at the conspiracy had this problem was when NEW ICONS was
running so try switching it off , removing it from WBstartup or if it runs
from Startup-Sequence or user-Startup edit it, put a ; in front of the line
and reboot your machine.

*Note From Mack* I actually run Graphic Workbench & NewIcons at the same
time, it really just depends on what backdrop you have installed i.e. I'm
running the Nova backdrop while running NewIcons with no problem, but i am
aware that on some backdrop sets NewIcons can cause a problem. The solution,
yes there is one, although not particualarly user friendly. First step,
switch of NewIcons then install the backdrop set of your choice, then using
an icon editing program such as "Iconian" save your disk.info's as brushes.
Now switch NewIcons back on & reboot. Having rebooted you now want to run
your icon editor again, load in the brushes of your disk.info's and they
will remap themselves to uneffected colours, then just save them as
disk.info's to the relevant partitions and as if by Magic....
I hope this helps you & with a little time & patience all problems can be
overcome.

                           @{ "BACK TO PROBLEM PAGE" link problems }

@endnode
@node edit "EDIT STARTUP-SEQUENCE or USER_STARTUP"
   Open up a shell window found in sys:systems and copy the file you want to
edit just incase it goes wrong
 type copy sys:s/startup-sequence to sys:s/oldstartup
 press return 
 {{this copies and renames startup-sequence as oldstartup}}
 now type edit sys:s/startup-sequence
 press return
 once you have made the changes press the esc key then the x key then return
you have now alterd startup-sequence reboot the machine
if you wish your old startup-sequence back open shell
type s and press return
type rename oldstartup to startup-sequence press return




                           @{ "BACK TO RAM.ICON" link ramicon}
@endnode
